# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sunburst-icicle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] In graph drawing, a **circular layout** is a style of drawing that places the vertices of a graph on a circle, often evenly spaced so that they form the vertices of a regular polygon.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] Circular layouts are a good fit for communications network topologies such as star or ring networks, and for the cyclic parts of metabolic networks.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] For graphs with a known Hamiltonian cycle, a circular layout allows the cycle to be depicted as the circle, and in this way circular layouts form the basis of the LCF notation for Hamiltonian cubic graphs.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] A circular layout may be used on its own for an entire graph drawing, but it also may be used as the layout for smaller clusters of vertices within a larger graph drawing, such as its biconnected components, clusters of genes in a gene interaction graph, or natural subgroups within a social network.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] If multiple vertex circles are used in this way, other methods such as force-directed graph drawing may be used to arrange the clusters.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] The edges of the drawing may be depicted as chords of the circle, as circular arcs (possibly perpendicular to the vertex circle, so that the edges model lines of the Poincaré disk model of hyperbolic geometry), or as other types of curve.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] The visual distinction between the inside and the outside of the vertex circle in a circular layout may be used to separate two different styles of edge drawing.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] For instance, a circular drawing algorithm of Gansner & Koren (2007) uses edge bundling within the circle, together with some edges that are not bundled, drawn outside the circle.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] For circular layouts of regular graphs, with edges drawn both inside and outside as circular arcs, the angle of incidence of one of these arcs with the vertex circle is the same at both ends of the arc, a property that simplifies the optimization of the angular resolution of the drawing.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] Several authors have studied the problem of finding a permutation of the vertices of a circular layout that minimizes the number of edge crossings when all edges are drawn inside the vertex circle.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] This number of crossings is zero only for outerplanar graphs.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] For other graphs, it may be optimized or reduced separately for each biconnected component of the graph before combining the solutions, as these components may be drawn so that they do not interact.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] In general, minimizing the number of crossings is NP-complete.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] (1995) described an approximation algorithm based on balanced cuts or edge separators, subsets of few edges whose removal disconnects the given graph into two subgraphs with approximately equal numbers of vertices.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] After finding an approximate cut, their algorithm arranges the two subgraphs on each side of the cut recursively, without considering the additional crossings formed by the edges that cross the cut.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] Their work cites a paper by Fan Chung and Shing-Tung Yau from 1994 that claimed $\rho =O(1)$ , but this was later found to have an erroneous proof.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] Instead, the best approximation known for the balanced cut problem has $\rho =O({\sqrt {\log n}})$ , giving this circular layout algorithm an approximation ratio of $O(\log ^{3}n)$ on graphs that have a large number of crossings relative to their vertex degrees.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] Heuristic methods for reducing the crossing complexity have also been devised, based e.g. on a careful vertex insertion order and on local optimization.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] A circular layout may also be used to maximize the number of crossings.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] In particular, choosing a random permutation for the vertices causes each possible crossing to occur with probability 1/3, so the expected number of crossings is within a factor of three of the maximum number of crossings among all possible layouts.
[src:sunburst-icicle/circular-layout] Derandomizing this method gives a deterministic approximation algorithm with approximation ratio three.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] In data mining and statistics, **hierarchical clustering** (also called **hierarchical cluster analysis** or **HCA**) is a method of cluster analysis that seeks to build a hierarchy of clusters.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] In general, the merges and splits are determined in a greedy manner.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The results of hierarchical clustering are usually presented in a dendrogram.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Hierarchical clustering has the distinct advantage that any valid measure of distance can be used.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] In fact, the observations themselves are not required: all that is used is a matrix of distances.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] On the other hand, except for the special case of single-linkage distance, none of the algorithms (except exhaustive search in ${\mathcal {O}}(2^{n})$ ) can be guaranteed to find the optimum solution.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The standard algorithm for **hierarchical agglomerative clustering** (HAC) has a time complexity of ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ and requires $\Omega (n^{2})$ memory, which makes it too slow for even medium data sets.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] However, for some special cases, optimal efficient agglomerative methods (of complexity ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ ) are known: **SLINK** for single-linkage and CLINK for complete-linkage clustering.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] With a heap, the runtime of the general case can be reduced to ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2}\log n)$ instead of ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ , at the cost of additional the memory requirements.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] In many cases, the memory overheads of this approach are too large to make it practically usable.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Methods exist which use quadtrees that demonstrate ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ total running time with ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ space.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Divisive clustering with an exhaustive search is ${\mathcal {O}}(2^{n})$ , but it is common to use faster heuristics to choose splits, such as *k*-means.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] While the linkage criterion determines how dissimilarity between sets of observations is computed, the underlying distance metric determines how dissimilarity between individual observations is measured.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Because hierarchical clustering permits any valid measure of distance, the choice of metric is guided by the nature of the data and can have a significant effect on the resulting clustering.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] It is often preferred when features are measured on different scales or when the data contain outliers, as it is less sensitive to large deviations than Euclidean distance.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Because it disregards vector magnitude, it is frequently used in text mining and document clustering, where documents are represented as high-dimensional term-frequency vectors.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Unlike Euclidean distance, it is scale-invariant and is useful when features are correlated or measured in different units.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The choice of metric interacts with the choice of linkage criterion.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] For example, Ward's method and centroid-based linkages are defined in terms of squared Euclidean distances, whereas single-linkage and complete-linkage clustering can be used with any valid metric.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] In order to decide which clusters should be combined (for agglomerative), or where a cluster should be split (for divisive), a measure of dissimilarity between sets of observations is required.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The choice of metric as well as linkage can have a major impact on the result of the clustering, where the lower level metric determines which objects are most similar, whereas the linkage criterion influences the shape of the clusters.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] For example, complete-linkage tends to produce more spherical clusters than single-linkage.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The linkage criterion determines the distance between sets of observations as a function of the pairwise distances between observations.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Some of these can only be recomputed recursively (WPGMA, WPGMC), for many a recursive computation with Lance-Williams-equations is more efficient, while for other (Hausdorff, Medoid) the distances have to be computed with the slower full formula.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The choice of linkage criterion significantly affects the shape and quality of the resulting clusters.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Each method has distinct strengths and weaknesses depending on the structure of the data.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The naive implementation of agglomerative hierarchical clustering has a time complexity of O(*n*³) and a space complexity of O(*n*²), where *n* is the number of data points, because at each of the *n* − 1 merge steps the algorithm must search and update an *n* × *n* proximity matrix.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] For single linkage, optimized algorithms based on minimum spanning trees reduce the time complexity to O(*n*² log *n*).
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] For other linkage criteria, the use of priority queues and nearest-neighbor chains can also achieve O(*n*² log *n*) time in practice.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Hausdorff linkage is a hierarchical clustering criterion based on the Hausdorff distance, a metric defined between sets of points in a given metric space.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Unlike standard linkage methods that rely on pairwise distances between individual observations, Hausdorff linkage evaluates distances between entire clusters, thereby incorporating information about their geometric structure.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Formally, let $(S,\delta )$ be a metric space, and let A and B be nonempty compact subsets of S .
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] This definition captures the largest distance from a point in one set to the closest point in the other set.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Equivalently, it can be interpreted as the smallest radius r such that every point of A lies within distance r of some point in B , and every point of B lies within distance r of some point in A .
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] In this sense, the Hausdorff distance measures the maximum mismatch between two sets.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] In hierarchical clustering, Hausdorff linkage uses $d_{H}(A,B)$ as the dissimilarity measure between clusters.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Initially, each data point forms its own cluster, and the Hausdorff distance between singleton sets reduces to the original metric.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] At each step, the two clusters with the smallest Hausdorff distance are merged, and distances are recomputed using the same set-based definition.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] This iterative process continues until all points belong to a single cluster, producing a hierarchical structure (dendrogram).
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Compared to other linkage criteria such as single, complete, or average linkage, Hausdorff linkage operates on a set-to-set basis rather than relying solely on pairwise point distances.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] As a result, it captures the global geometry of clusters and can better preserve structural features of the data.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] It has been shown to provide behavior intermediate between single and complete linkage, avoiding the chaining effect of the former while reducing the tendency of the latter to overestimate distances between clusters.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] However, these advantages come with increased computational cost.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Computing the Hausdorff distance between two clusters typically requires evaluating distances between all pairs of points across the sets, often via a max–min procedure over a distance matrix.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] This makes Hausdorff linkage more computationally expensive than simpler linkage criteria, particularly for large datasets.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Overall, Hausdorff linkage provides a mathematically well-founded clustering approach that is effective for distinguishing complex structures in data.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] For example, suppose this data is to be clustered, and the Euclidean distance is the distance metric.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Cutting the tree at a given height will give a partitioning clustering at a selected precision.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] In this example, cutting after the second row (from the top) of the dendrogram will yield clusters {a} {b c} {d e} {f}.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Cutting after the third row will yield clusters {a} {b c} {d e f}, which is a coarser clustering, with a smaller number but larger clusters.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The clustering process can also be illustrated step-by-step to show how the dendrogram is constructed from the underlying data.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] In this visualization, each point begins as its own cluster.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] At each step, the two clusters with the smallest distance between them are merged.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] On the left, dashed lines indicate which clusters are combined, and a running list of cluster groupings shows how clusters evolve over time.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] On the right, the dendrogram is constructed simultaneously, with each merge represented by a new branch.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The height of each merge in the dendrogram corresponds to the distance or dissimilarity between the clusters being combined.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Merges that occur at lower heights represent clusters that are more similar, while merges at higher heights indicate greater dissimilarity.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Color-coding is used to associate each merge step in the data visualization with its corresponding branch in the dendrogram.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] A key aspect of interpreting a dendrogram is understanding the meaning of branch height.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The height at which two clusters are joined represents the distance or dissimilarity between those clusters, where lower merges indicate greater similarity and higher merges indicate greater dissimilarity.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Early merges at lower heights reflect the closest relationships between observations, while later merges combine increasingly different groups.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] When the dendrogram is scaled using actual or normalized distances, the vertical spacing between merges provides insight into the relative differences between clusters.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Large vertical gaps between successive merges often indicate meaningful separations in the data.and can help guide the selection of cluster boundaries, although dendrograms alone should not be used to definitively determine the number of clusters.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Because dendrograms summarize underlying distance relationships, some information may be lost in the visualization, and interpretations are generally most reliable for clusters that merge at lower heights.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] In hierarchical clustering, the number of clusters is not determined automatically and must be chosen by analyzing the dendrogram.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] A common approach is to “cut” the dendrogram at a selected height, which partitions the data into clusters based on where the cut intersects the tree structure.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The choice of cut level has a significant impact on the resulting clustering.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] One widely used heuristic is to identify large vertical gaps in the dendrogram, which correspond to substantial increases in the distance between successive merges.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Cutting the dendrogram at a height just before such a gap can produce clusters that reflect natural groupings in the data.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] This is based on the observation that merges occurring at much larger distances often combine dissimilar clusters.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] In practice, the selection of the number of clusters may also depend on domain knowledge or application-specific requirements.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Quantitative measures such as the silhouette coefficient can be used to evaluate the quality of different clusterings.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Because hierarchical clustering is sensitive to the choice of distance metric and linkage criterion, the optimal number of clusters may vary depending on these factors.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] This method builds the hierarchy from the individual elements by progressively merging clusters.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] In our example, we have six elements {a} {b} {c} {d} {e} and {f}.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The first step is to determine which elements to merge in a cluster.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Usually, we want to take the two closest elements, according to the chosen distance.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Optionally, one can also construct a distance matrix at this stage, where the number in the *i*-th row *j*-th column is the distance between the *i*-th and *j*-th elements.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Then, as clustering progresses, rows and columns are merged as the clusters are merged and the distances updated.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] This is a common way to implement this type of clustering, and has the benefit of caching distances between clusters.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] A simple agglomerative clustering algorithm is described in the single-linkage clustering page; it can easily be adapted to different types of linkage (see below).
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Suppose we have merged the two closest elements *b* and *c*, we now have the following clusters {*a*}, {*b*, *c*}, {*d*}, {*e*} and {*f*}, and want to merge them further.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] To do that, we need to take the distance between {a} and {b c}, and therefore define the distance between two clusters.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] In case of tied minimum distances, a pair is randomly chosen, thus being able to generate several structurally different dendrograms.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Alternatively, all tied pairs may be joined at the same time, generating a unique dendrogram.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] One can always decide to stop clustering when there is a sufficiently small number of clusters (number criterion).
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Some linkages may also guarantee that agglomeration occurs at a greater distance between clusters than the previous agglomeration, and then one can stop clustering when the clusters are too far apart to be merged (distance criterion).
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] However, this is not the case of, e.g., the centroid linkage where the so-called reversals (inversions, departures from ultrametricity) may occur.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The basic principle of divisive clustering was published as the DIANA (DIvisive ANAlysis clustering) algorithm.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Initially, all data is in the same cluster, and the largest cluster is split until every object is separate.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Because there exist $O(2^{n})$ ways of splitting each cluster, heuristics are needed.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] DIANA chooses the object with the maximum average dissimilarity and then moves all objects to this cluster that are more similar to the new cluster than to the remainder.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Informally, DIANA is not so much a process of "dividing" as it is of "hollowing out": each iteration, an existing cluster (e.g. the initial cluster of the entire dataset) is chosen to form a new cluster inside of it.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Objects progressively move to this nested cluster, and hollow out the existing cluster.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Eventually, all that's left inside a cluster is nested clusters that grew there, without it owning any loose objects by itself.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] As long as $C_{*}$ isn't empty, keep migrating objects from $C_{*}$ to add them to $C_{\textrm {new}}$ .
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Intuitively, $D(i)$ above measures how strongly an object wants to leave its current cluster, but it is attenuated when the object wouldn't fit in the splinter group either.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Such objects will likely start their own splinter group eventually.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The dendrogram of DIANA can be constructed by letting the splinter group $C_{\textrm {new}}$ be a child of the hollowed-out cluster $C_{*}$ each time.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] This constructs a tree with $C_{0}$ as its root and n unique single-object clusters as its leaves.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Standard hierarchical agglomerative clustering is difficult to apply to very large datasets because typical implementations require substantial memory for pairwise structures and can scale poorly as n grows (see § Complexity above).
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] In computational biology, single-cell technologies such as mass cytometry routinely produce tens of millions of high-dimensional observations, which motivates specialized workflows that preserve biological resolution without requiring that every expensive step be run on the full matrix at once.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The figure summarizes the HAL-x workflow: dimensionality reduction for density estimation, density-based seed clusters, a supervised linkage graph between clusters, and successive merges to a chosen generalization threshold.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] This design targets scalability: expensive steps are deliberately restricted to manageable downscaled subsamples, while label prediction can be applied broadly to the full dataset once the hierarchy and classifiers are established.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] Because of this, HAL-x is extremely useful when hierarchical clustering requires minimal RAM.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] A practical limitation, common to embedding-first pipelines, is that low-dimensional representations can distort global geometry and reduce accuracy.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The HAL-x paper discusses when auxiliary preprocessing such as PCA may help for correlated features.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] HAL-x was motivated by workflows in which biologists need many related clusterings at different granularities (for example to preserve rare leukocyte subsets while still summarizing abundant lineages) without repeatedly training separate models from scratch on millions of cells.
[src:sunburst-icicle/hierarchical-clustering] The authors report analyses on large cytometry-style datasets where rapid, tunable clusterings are used to support downstream interpretation of cellular phenotypes across conditions.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] The **nested set model** is a technique for representing nested set collections (also known as trees or hierarchies) in relational databases.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] It is based on Nested Intervals, that "are immune to hierarchy reorganization problem, and allow answering ancestor path hierarchical queries algorithmically — without accessing the stored hierarchy relation".
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] The standard relational algebra and relational calculus, and the SQL operations based on them, are unable to express directly all desirable operations on hierarchies.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] The nested set model is a solution to that problem.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] An alternative solution is the expression of the hierarchy as a parent-child relation.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] Joe Celko called this the adjacency list model.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] If the hierarchy can have arbitrary depth, the adjacency list model does not allow the expression of operations such as comparing the contents of hierarchies of two elements, or determining whether an element is somewhere in the subhierarchy of another element.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] When the hierarchy is of fixed or bounded depth, the operations are possible, but expensive, due to the necessity of performing one relational join per level.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] This is often known as the bill of materials problem.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] Hierarchies may be expressed easily by switching to a graph database.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] When these solutions are not available or not feasible, another approach must be taken.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] The nested set model is to number the nodes according to a tree traversal, which visits each node twice, assigning numbers in the order of visiting, and at both visits.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] This leaves two numbers for each node, which are stored as two attributes.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] Querying becomes inexpensive: hierarchy membership can be tested by comparing these numbers.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] Updating requires renumbering and is therefore expensive.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] Refinements that use rational numbers instead of integers can avoid renumbering, and so are faster to update, although much more complicated.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] The "Clothing" category, with the highest position in the hierarchy, encompasses all subordinating categories.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] It is therefore given left and right domain values of 1 and 22, the latter value being the double of the total number of nodes being represented.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] The next hierarchical level contains "Men's" and "Women's", both containing levels within themselves that must be accounted for.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] Each level's data node is assigned left and right domain values according to the number of sublevels contained within, as shown in the table data.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] Queries using nested sets can be expected to be faster than queries using a stored procedure to traverse an adjacency list, and so are the faster option for databases which lack native recursive query constructs, such as MySQL 5.x.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] However, recursive SQL queries can be expected to perform comparably for 'find immediate descendants' queries, and much faster for other depth search queries, and so are the faster option for databases which provide them, such as PostgreSQL, Oracle, and Microsoft SQL Server.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] MySQL used to lack recursive query constructs but added such features in version 8.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] The use case for a dynamic endless database tree hierarchy is rare.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] The Nested Set model is appropriate where the tree element and one or two attributes are the only data, but is a poor choice when more complex relational data exists for the elements in the tree.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] Given an arbitrary starting depth for a category of 'Vehicles' and a child of 'Cars' with a child of 'Mercedes', a foreign key table relationship must be established unless the tree table is natively non-normalized.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] Attributes of a newly created tree item may not share all attributes with a parent, child or even a sibling.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] If a foreign key table is established for a table of 'Plants' attributes, no integrity is given to the child attribute data of 'Trees' and its child 'Oak'.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] Therefore, in each case of an item inserted into the tree, a foreign key table of the item's attributes must be created for all but the most trivial of use cases.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] For more complex systems, hierarchy can be developed through relational models rather than an implicit numeric tree structure.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] Depth of an item is simply another attribute rather than the basis for an entire DB architecture.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] The model doesn't allow for multiple parent categories.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] For example, an 'Oak' could be a child of 'Tree-Type', but also 'Wood-Type'.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] An additional tagging or taxonomy has to be established to accommodate this, again leading to a design more complex than a straightforward fixed model.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] Nested sets are very slow for inserts because it requires updating left and right domain values for all records in the table after the insert.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] This can cause a lot of database stress as many rows are rewritten and indexes rebuilt.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] However, if it is possible to store a forest of small trees in table instead of a single big tree, the overhead may be significantly reduced, since only one small tree must be updated.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] The nested interval model does not suffer from this problem, but is more complex to implement, and is not as well known.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] It still suffers from the relational foreign-key table problem.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] The nested interval model stores the position of the nodes as rational numbers expressed as quotients (n/d).
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] Using the nested set model as described above has some performance limitations during certain tree traversal operations.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] The query will be more complicated when searching for children more than one level deep.
[src:sunburst-icicle/nested-set-model] To overcome this limitation and simplify tree traversal an additional column is added to the model to maintain the depth of a node within a tree.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] A **radial tree**, or **radial map**, is a method of displaying a tree structure (e.g., a tree data structure) in a way that expands outwards, radially.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] It is one of many ways to visually display a tree, with examples dating back to the early 20th century.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] In use, it is a type of information graphic.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] The overall distance "d" is the distance between levels of the graph.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] It is chosen so that the overall layout will fit within a screen.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] Layouts are generated by working outward from the center, root.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] The first level is a special case because all the nodes have the same parent.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] The nodes for level 1 can be distributed evenly, or weighted depending on the number of children they have.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] For subsequent levels, the children are positioned within sectors of the remaining space, so that child nodes of one parent do not overlap with others.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] There are many extensions to this algorithm to create more visually balanced layouts, to allow users to navigate from node to node (changing the center), or accommodate node labels and combine force-directed layouts with radial layouts.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] The layout has some similarities to a hyperbolic tree, though a key difference is that hyperbolic trees are based on hyperbolic geometry, whereas in a radial tree the distance between orbits is relatively linear.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] In a simple case, the first node is at the top, and the linked nodes are beneath.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] As each node typically has more than one child, the resulting shape is relatively triangular.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] In a radial layout, instead of each successive generation being displayed a row below, each generation is displayed in a new, outer orbit.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] Since the length of each orbit increases with the radius, there tends to be more room for the nodes.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] A radial tree will spread the larger number of nodes over a larger area as the levels increase.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] We use the terms level and depth interchangeably.
[src:sunburst-icicle/radial-tree] Nevertheless, the number of nodes increases exponentially with the distance from the first node, whereas the circumference of each orbit increases linearly, so, by the outer orbits, the nodes tend to be packed together.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] A **pie chart** (or a **circle chart**) is a circular statistical graphic which is divided into slices to illustrate numerical proportion.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] In a pie chart, the arc length of each slice (and consequently its central angle and area) is proportional to the quantity it represents.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] While it is named for its resemblance to a pie which has been sliced, there are variations on the way it can be presented.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The earliest known pie chart is generally credited to William Playfair's *Statistical Breviary* of 1801.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Pie charts are very widely used in the business world and the mass media.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] However, they have been criticized, and many experts recommend avoiding them, as research has shown it is more difficult to make simple comparisons such as the size of different sections of a given pie chart, or to compare data across different pie charts.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Some research has shown pie charts perform well for comparing complex combinations of sections (e.g., "A + B vs.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Commonly recommended alternatives to pie charts in most cases include bar charts, box plots, and dot plots.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The earliest known pie chart is generally credited to William Playfair's *Statistical Breviary* of 1801, in which two such graphs are used.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Playfair presented an illustration, which contained a series of pie charts.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] One of those charts depicted the proportions of the Turkish Empire located in Asia, Europe and Africa before 1789.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] This invention was not widely used at first.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Playfair thought that pie charts were in need of a third dimension to add additional information.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Florence Nightingale may not have invented the pie chart, but she adapted it to make it more readable, which fostered its wide use, still today.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Nightingale reconfigured the pie chart making the length of the wedges variable instead of their width.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The graph, then, resembled a cock's comb.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] She was later assumed to have created it due to the obscurity and lack of practicality of Playfair's creation.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The French engineer Charles Joseph Minard also used pie charts, in 1858.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] A map of his from 1858 used pie charts to represent the cattle sent from all around France for consumption in Paris.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] A 3D pie chart, or perspective pie chart, is used to give the chart a 3D look.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Often used for aesthetic reasons, the third dimension does not improve the reading of the data; on the contrary, these plots are difficult to interpret because of the distorted effect of perspective associated with the third dimension.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The use of superfluous dimensions not used to display the data of interest is discouraged for charts in general, not only for pie charts.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] A doughnut chart (also spelled donut) is a variant of the pie chart, with a blank center allowing for additional information about the data as a whole to be included.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Doughnut charts are similar to pie charts in that their aim is to illustrate proportions.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] This type of circular graph can support multiple statistics at once and it provides a better data intensity ratio than standard pie charts.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] It does not have to contain information in the center.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] A chart with one or more sectors separated from the rest of the disk is known as an *exploded pie chart*.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] This effect is used to either highlight a sector, or to highlight smaller segments of the chart with small proportions.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The polar area diagram is similar to a usual pie chart, except sectors have equal angles and differ rather in how far each sector extends from the center of the circle.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] It is used to plot cyclic phenomena (e.g., counts of deaths by month).
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] For example, if the counts of deaths in each month for a year are to be plotted then there will be 12 sectors (one per month) all with the same angle of 30 degrees each.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The radius of each sector would be proportional to the square root of the death rate for the month, so the area of a sector represents the rate of deaths in a month.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] If the death rate in each month is subdivided by cause of death, it is possible to make multiple comparisons on one diagram, as is seen in the polar area diagram famously developed by Florence Nightingale.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The first known use of polar area diagrams was by André-Michel Guerry, which he called *courbes circulaires* (circular curves), in an 1829 paper showing seasonal and daily variation in wind direction over the year and births and deaths by hour of the day.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Léon Lalanne later used a polar diagram to show the frequency of wind directions around compass points in 1843.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The wind rose is still used by meteorologists.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Nightingale published her rose diagram in 1858.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Although the name "coxcomb" has come to be associated with this type of diagram, Nightingale originally used the term to refer to the publication in which this diagram first appeared—an attention-getting book of charts and tables—rather than to this specific type of diagram.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] A ring chart, also known as a sunburst chart or a multilevel pie chart, is used to visualize hierarchical data, depicted by concentric circles.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The circle in the center represents the root node, with the hierarchy moving outward from the center.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] A segment of the inner circle bears a hierarchical relationship to those segments of the outer circle which lie within the angular sweep of the parent segment.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] A variant of the polar area chart is the spie chart, designed by Dror Feitelson.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The design superimposes a normal pie chart with a modified polar area chart to permit the comparison of two sets of related data.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The base pie chart represents the first data set in the usual way, with different slice sizes.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The second set is represented by the superimposed polar area chart, using the same angles as the base, and adjusting the radii to fit the data.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] For example, the base pie chart could show the distribution of age and gender groups in a population, and the overlay their representation among road casualties.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Age and gender groups that are especially susceptible to being involved in accidents then stand out as slices that extend beyond the original pie chart.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Square charts, also called waffle charts, are a form of pie charts that use squares instead of circles to represent percentages.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Similar to basic circular pie charts, square pie charts take each percentage out of a total 100%.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] They are often 10 by 10 grids, where each cell represents 1%.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Despite the name, circles, pictograms (such as of people), and other shapes may be used instead of squares.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] One major benefit to square charts is that smaller percentages, difficult to see on traditional pie charts, can be easily depicted.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The following example chart is based on preliminary results of the election for the European Parliament in 2004.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The table lists the number of seats allocated to each party group, along with the derived percentage of the total that they each make up.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The values in the last column, the derived central angle of each sector, is found by taking that percentage of 360.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] The size of each central angle is proportional to the size of the corresponding quantity, here the number of seats.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Since the sum of the central angles has to be 360°, the central angle for a quantity that is a fraction *Q* of the total is 360*Q* degrees.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] In the example, the central angle for the largest group (European People's Party (EPP)) is 135.7° because 0.377 times 360, rounded to one decimal place, equals 135.7.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] A flaw exhibited by pie charts is that they cannot show more than a few values without separating the visual encoding (the “slices”) from the data they represent (typically percentages).
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] When slices become too small, pie charts have to rely on colors, textures or arrows so the reader can understand them.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] This makes them unsuitable for use with larger amounts of data.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Pie charts also take up a larger amount of space on the page compared to the more flexible bar charts, which do not need to have separate legends, and can display other values such as averages or targets at the same time.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Statisticians generally regard pie charts as a poor method of displaying information, and they are uncommon in scientific literature.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] One reason is that it is more difficult for comparisons to be made between the size of items in a chart when area is used instead of length and when different items are shown as different shapes.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Further, in research performed at AT&T Bell Laboratories, it was shown that comparison by angle was less accurate than comparison by length.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Most subjects have difficulty ordering the slices in the pie chart by size; when an equivalent bar chart is used the comparison is much easier.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Similarly, comparisons between data sets are easier using the bar chart.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] However, if the goal is to compare a given category (a slice of the pie) with the total (the whole pie) in a single chart and the multiple is close to 25 or 50 percent, then a pie chart can often be more effective than a bar graph.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] In a pie chart with many sections, several values may be represented with the same or similar colors, making interpretation difficult.
[src:sunburst-icicle/sunburst-chart] Several studies presented at the European Visualization Conference analyzed the relative accuracy of several pie chart formats, reaching the conclusion that pie charts and doughnut charts produce similar error levels when reading them, and square pie charts provide the most accurate reading.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] A **tree structure**, **tree diagram**, or **tree model** is a way of representing the hierarchical nature of a structure in a graphical form.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] It is named a "tree structure" because the classic representation resembles a tree, although the chart is generally upside down compared to a biological tree, with the "stem" at the top and the "leaves" at the bottom.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] A tree structure is conceptual, and appears in several forms.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] For a discussion of tree structures in specific fields, see Tree (data structure) for computer science; insofar as it relates to graph theory, see tree (graph theory) or tree (set theory).
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] Other related articles are listed below.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] The lines connecting elements are called "branches".
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] Nodes without children are called leaf nodes, "end-nodes", or "leaves".
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] Every finite tree structure has a member that has no superior.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] This member is called the "root" or root node.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] But the converse is not true: infinite tree structures may or may not have a root node.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] The names of relationships between nodes model the kinship terminology of family relations.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] The gender-neutral names "parent" and "child" have largely displaced the older "father" and "son" terminology.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] The term "uncle" is still widely used for other nodes at the same level as the parent, although it is sometimes replaced with gender-neutral terms like "ommer".
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] In the example, "encyclopedia" is the parent of "science" and "culture", its children.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] "Art" and "craft" are siblings, and children of "culture", which is their parent and thus one of their ancestors.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] Also, "encyclopedia", as the root of the tree, is the ancestor of "science", "culture", "art" and "craft".
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] Finally, "science", "art" and "craft", as leaves, are ancestors of no other node.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] The Oxford English Dictionary records use of both the terms "tree structure" and "tree-diagram" from 1965 in Noam Chomsky's *Aspects of the Theory of Syntax*.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] In a tree structure there is one and only one path from any point to any other point.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] For a formal definition see set theory, and for a generalization in which children are not necessarily successors, see prefix order.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] There are many ways of visually representing tree structures.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] Layered "icicle" diagrams that use alignment/adjacency.
[src:sunburst-icicle/tree-structure] Lists or diagrams that use indentation, sometimes called "outlines" or "tree views".
